Section 2: Peakiness Detection (vtpeakpy)¶

In section 2, the task is to explore a python program called vtpeakpy. Vtpeakpy is a automatic thresholding python program which will accept an image input and output the thresholded image. The algorithm is that it will detect two of the main peaks in the histogram of the input image and the threshold will be the lowest minimum histogram value between the two histogram peaks. Another input to the program is the "d" parameter, which stands for the minimum histogram bins distance between the two peaks. This is to prevent the second largest histogram value to be the one next to it, which would cause an inaccurate threshold selection. The vtpeakpy program is tested on 4 different images: mp.vx, facsimile, map, and shtl.vx. The input and output images are displayed and discussed below:

The vtpeakpy program is tested in all four images above and their output is shown right below the original image. For each of the images, several "d" parameter are tested to make sure that thresholded most accurately. Choosing the right "d" value may be tricky, but this is done by referring to the histogram. The histogram can be accessed through "Tools -> Image Histogram" in vview. From the image histogram, we can see the two peaks of the bimodal histogram with a deep valley in between. If a distance is not chosen right or is too small, the second highest bin may still be in the same peak region of the bimodal histogram. As a result, the threshold chosen by the algorithm may not be ideal and the output thresholded image produced may not be good.

The first test image that was used is the map image. In order to best segment the image, the right "d" input needs to be found. The first step is to analyze the histogram (shown in Figure 1). From the histogram, we can see that the two peaks of the bimodal histogram are at around pixel value of 40 and 130. The valley between the two peaks is at around 60. In order to achieve the next max bin to be around 40, instead of still in the region of 130, a larger "d" needs to be chosen. After trials and errors, a "d" value of 70 is chosen and the threshold used is 64, which will be the optimal value from this algorithm. This technique of choosing the "d" value based on the histogram is being done for all of the test images.

From the outputs of the images tested in vtpeakpy, we can see that these images are not be segmented perfectly. The advantage of this algorithm is that it is very simple. It will simply choose the lowest histogram bin value between two peaks of the histogram. This will work well if the image is of a bimodal histogram, in which a valley can be clearly detected between two peaks of histogram bin region. It will also work well if the entire object or objects have a similar range of pixel value that is significantly different to the background's pixel value. The disadvantage of this algorithm is that a wrong threshold value may be chosen because of noise or false second-peak. This results to an imperfect image segmentation. In order to prevent this, the user may need to choose right "d" to be supplied to the program and this may be tedious for most users. This algorithm will also not work well when there are a lot of empty histogram bins, which means that there is just not enough data to process. The image may also need some smoothing to allow a more accurate threshold to be chosen. Another weakness of this algorithm is that a single threshold value may not be able to represent the whole image. An example is clearly shown in Figure 6, where when the threshold is chosen, it blacked out the outer part of the image and ended up making part of the map invisible. The process of image segmentation became harmful for the user. Overall, this algorithm is not robust.

Section 3: Iterative Threshold Selection (vits)¶

In section 3, the task is to create an automatic thresholding program that will perform an iterative thresholding. This program will be named vits and it will be built off the code of vtpeakpy but with several changes. The way this iterative algorithm works is that it will first either receive an initial threshold to try from the user or it will calculate a threshold value from the average gray value of the entire image. Then, the histogram will be separated into two different regions and an average or mean gray value for each region is calculated. Then, the average between these two averages will be used as the new threshold value. This algorithm will continue to iterate until the average of the two regions or the threshold calculation no longer changes. This means that the threshold calculation has converged to an optimal point. Since the threshold value is derived from the averages across the entire histogram, this means that the entire image data is being considered for this threshold calculation, allowing a more robust algorithm.

This program starts by getting the "t" user input, which determines the initial threshold value to be tested. If this value is provided, it will first be verified that the value is within the histogram range, which is between 0 to 255. If the value did not past the requirement or is not provided, then the average gray value of the image will be calculated as used as the initial threshold value. This is done by iterating each pixel of the image, summing up the pixel value and total number of pixels, then dividing the total pixel value with pixel count to get the average pixel value (or gray value).

Next, histogram bins is created by using numpy zeros function. An iteration through each image pixel is done to fill up each histogram bin with the corresponding pixel value count. Then, an "average" function definition, which accepts a low and high input, is created. This function will calculate the average gray value between the low and high range of histogram bins. An iteration is used in the range of the low and high bin value and during each iteration two calculation is done. First calculation is to iteratively sum the multiplication of pixel count in each bin with the bin value itself (bin value being the gray value that it represents). Second calculation is to iteratively sum the bin value. After getting the result of these two iterative calculations, the average bin value is calculated by dividing the multiplied value of pixel count and bin value with the sum of bin values. This average value became the output of the function.

Since this is an iterative algorithm, a while loop is used to perform this iterative calculations. This while loop will continue executing while the previous and current average value calculation of the two regions still changes. In order to do this, a total of four variables are used to store the average values: a previous and current average value for each of the region. Going into the loop, the first step is to update the previous average variable with the current value. Then, a midpoint is defined as the rounded up value of the threshold value. It is rounded up as it may be a float number. Using the midpoint value, two average values of the two regions are calculated using the "average" function that has been programmed. One region will go form 0 to the midpoint and the other will go from midpoint to value of 255. From the two averages calculated, the threshold value for the iteration will be the average of the two. This iteration will continue until the threshold value converges to an ontimum value. At the end of the program, similar to the vtpeakpy, an iteration through all pixels are done to change their values to either 0 or 255 based on the threshold value.

The main advantage of this algorithm is that all of the image data is being considered in determining the threshold. This is done by calculating using the two mean bin values of the two regions of the histogram that is separated by the a threshold value. By taking the entire image data into consideration, this makes the algorithm to be more robust compared to the vtpeakpy program used in section 3. As a result, it may be able to provide a better image segmentation for some images where vtpeakpy algorithm does not perform well.

The code for vits python program is below:

In [ ]:
#!/usr/bin/env python

"""
vits:  Iterative threshold selection algorithm
"""

import sys
import numpy as np
from numpy import *
from v4 import vx
import math

of=' '
vxif=' '
clist = vx.vxparse(sys.argv, "if= of= t= -v -")
exec (clist)

if 'OPT' in locals():
   print ("vits: iterative threshold selection algorithm")
   print ("if= input file")
   print ("of= output file")
   print ("t=  initial threshold (default is average gray value)")
   print ("-v  (verbose) print threshold information")
   exit(0)

optv = 'OPTv' in locals()

inimage = vx.Vx(vxif)
im = inimage.i
if im.dtype != uint8 :
    print ("error: image not byte type", file=sys.stderr)
    exit(1)

thresh = 0

if 't' in locals(): 
  t_in = int(t)
  if t_in < 0 or t_in > 255:
      print("t= must be between 0 and 255", file=sys.stderr)
  else: # If threshold input is suitable, use it
	  thresh = t_in
else: # If threshold is not defined by user
    total_pixel_value = 0
    pixel_count = 0
    for y in range(im.shape[0]):
        for x in range(im.shape[1]):
            total_pixel_value = total_pixel_value + im[y,x]
            pixel_count = pixel_count + 1
    thresh = total_pixel_value / pixel_count

# Create a blank histogram of 256 bins
hist = np.zeros(256)

# Compute the histogram
for y in range(im.shape[0]):
  for x in range(im.shape[1]):
    hist[im[y,x]]+=1
    
# Function to calculate average gray values between hist range
def average (low, high):
    ave = 0
    total_mult = 0
    total_pix = 0

    for i in range(low, high):
        total_mult = total_mult + (hist[i] * i)
        total_pix = total_pix + hist[i]

    ave = total_mult / total_pix
    return ave

avg1 = 0
avg2 = 0 
old1 = 1 # Differentiate to avg values to enter loop
old2 = 1

# Loop to determine threshold
while avg1 != old1 and avg2 != old2: # stop if avg1 and 2 is already equal
	# Update old average values
	old1 = avg1
	old2 = avg2
	
	# Determine the splitting value for histogram regions
	midpoint = math.ceil(thresh) # Round up
	
	# Calculate average gray values of the two regions
	avg1 = average(0, midpoint)
	avg2 = average(midpoint, 256)
	print(midpoint, avg1, avg2, thresh)
	# New thresh value
	thresh = (avg1 + avg2) / 2
  
# Print output for verbose mode
if (optv):
  print("thresh=",thresh, file=sys.stderr) 
  
# Apply threshold
for y in range(im.shape[0]):
  for x in range(im.shape[1]):
    if (im[y,x] >= thresh): 
      im[y,x] = 255
    else:
      im[y,x] = 0

vx.vfwrite(of, im)

Section 5: Region Growing (vgrow)¶

In section 5, another method of image segmentation is explored, which is region growing. In the previous sections it has been all about using thresholding for image segmentation. However, from the results above we can see that for some types of images using thresholding for image segmentation is not ideal. For those images, it may be better to use region growing.

Region growing is a method in which it will classify a group of pixels as a meaningful region if it passes the Homogeneity Criterion. This criteria may range from the grey level, or geometry (size and shape), or even topology. For the algorithm that is explored in this section, the criteria is the range of pixel value. The python program that will be created is vgrow. The algorithm will scan the entire image and group connected pixels that is within a pixel value range as a meaningful region. The output will be an image with the different regions. This program will be built based on the connected component labeling algorithm created in Lab2, which is cclabelpy. It will have a similar algorithm connected pixels and labeling them, but the program will not be making a distinction between foreground (pixel value above 0) or background (0-valued pixel), but will be classifying based on the pixel range and create regions from those information. Similar to cclabelpy program, this program will have a 4-foreground connectivity, in which the connected pixels that will be checked is only from four sides (top, bottom, left, and right).

This program will accept an integer "r" input from the user, which defines the pixel range to be used. This means that a group of connected pixels will be classified as a region if the deteced connected pixels are within this defined range to the first pixel detected. The user will also be able to choose between two labeling modes based on the "-p" input flag. If the "-p" flag is specified, the label of the region will be based on the first detected pixel value, which will allow the label to clearly represeng the region's pixel value. If the "-p" is not specified, then a sequential labeling pattern will be used (starting from 1, 2, 3...). One thing to note is that if the end of the label (255) has been reached, it will roll over to label 1.

This program starts by checking the "r" and "-p" input from the user. If the range "r" is received as input, a verification is done to ensure it is within 0 to 255. If the range does not pass this criteria or none is supplied, a default range of 10 will be used. Next, image im is loaded from the user input and a tm image is created as a duplicate of image im, but with a border of 1. This is to allow the algorithm to detect when the image edge has been reached (detecting zero-valued pixels). Through an iterative code through all pixels, image im is blacked out (pixel value = 0) to be used as a blank canvas for labeled output image.

Inside this program, there is a function definition "setlabel" that is adopted from "cclabelpy" program in Lab2. It accepts three parameters: "x" index, "y" index, and label number "n". This function will also read both the tm and im image, as well as the "first pixel" and "range" variables. The "first pixel" variable stores the pixel value of the first pixel detected for the region. This will be used along with the "range" variable as one of the criteria for the connected component labeling. This function will first set the label of the current pixel in the output im image. Then, it will attempt to recurse into 4 neighbours in the 4 sides (top, bottom, left, and right). Similar to the "cclabelpy" algorithm, the criteria is that the neigbour's pixel value needs to be above 0 and the pixel have not been labeled in the output image. However, there is another criteria that needs to be met for this algorithm. The difference between the neighbour pixel's value and the first pixel detected needs to be below the defined range allowed. If all three criteria are met, the recursive setlabel algorithm will be called into that neighbouring pixel. This function will be called in the main loop and it will recursively label all of connected pixels that passes the criteria with the same label.

The final section of this code is our main loop that iterates to every pixel in the original image (using embed image tm). There are two types of loops based on the "-p" flag: one that will label the region based on the first pixel and another that labels the region sequentially with a range from 1-255). In both cases, on every pixel, the loop will check on whether the current pixel has a value bigger than 0 and that it has not been labeled in the output im image. The "first pixel" variable will also be defined as the first pixel value detected. Then, the next part is where the "-p" flag came into effect. When "-p" flag is passed, the "label" passed into the "setlabel" function would be the "first pixel" value. Thus the output labels will be based on the first pixel value and would represeng the region well. On the other hand, when "-p" is not passed by the user, the label will start at 1, and it will be incremented for every region. This label will reset to 1 when it reaches the limit of 255. At the end of the day, the user will get to decide how they would want their image to be labeled. This would only change the label value and will not change the number of regions detected or the shape of each region.

This vgrow program, which is a region growing algorithm, is created to explore the performance of this type of image segmentation. The program will be tested with both small images and large images to test its edge cases. The result will be weighed the performance of this method.

The code for vgrow python program is below:

In [ ]:
#!/usr/bin/env python

""" vgrow a python region growing program
"""

import sys
from numpy  import *
from v4 import vx

of=' '
vxif=' '
clist = vx.vxparse(sys.argv,  "if= of= r= -p -v  - ")
exec (clist )

if 'OPT' in locals():
   print ("vgrow program")
   print ("if= input file")
   print ("of= output file")
   print ("r=  region pixel range")
   print ("-p  flag to select labeling scheme")
   print ("[-v] verbose mode")
   exit(0)

optp = 'OPTp' in locals()
optv = 'OPTv' in locals()

pixel_range = 0 # Initialize range variable
if 'r' in locals(): 
  print(r)
  r_in = int(r)
  if r_in < 0 or r_in > 255: # If r is not within range
      print("r= must be between 0 and 255", file=sys.stderr)
      pixel_range = 10 # Default range
  else: # If range input is suitable, use it
	  pixel_range = r_in

inimage = vx.Vx( vxif )
im = inimage.i
tmimage = vx.Vx( inimage ) 
tmimage.embedim((1,1,1,1))
tm = tmimage.i

# Clear image for output
for y in range(im.shape[0]):
    for x in range(im.shape[1]):
        im[y,x] = 0

first_pixel = 0 # Initialize variable to store value of first pixel

def setlabel (x, y, n): # n is current label
    global im, tm, first_pixel, r
    im[y,x] = n
    # 4 connected foreground 8 connected background
    if tm[y+2,x+1] > 0 and im[y+1,x] == 0 and (abs(int(tm[y+2,x+1]) - first_pixel) < pixel_range): # If pixel above current tm is foreground and not labeled in im
        setlabel(x, y+1, n)
    if tm[y,x+1] > 0 and im[y-1,x] == 0 and (abs(int(tm[y,x+1]) - first_pixel) < pixel_range): # If pixel below current tm is foreground and not labeled in im
        setlabel(x, y-1, n)
    if tm[y+1,x] > 0 and im[y,x-1] == 0 and (abs(int(tm[y+1,x]) - first_pixel) < pixel_range): # If pixel left of current tm is foreground and not labeled in im
        setlabel(x-1, y, n)
    if tm[y+1,x+2] > 0 and im[y,x+1] == 0 and (abs(int(tm[y+1,x+2]) - first_pixel) < pixel_range): # If pixel right current tm is foreground and not labeled in im
        setlabel(x+1, y, n)

l = 1 # Set initial label l to be 1
sys.setrecursionlimit(100000)
if optp:
    for y in range(im.shape[0]):
        for x in range(im.shape[1]):
            if tm[y+1,x+1] > 0 and im[y,x] == 0:
                first_pixel = int(tm[y+1,x+1]) # Set first pixel value
                setlabel(x, y, first_pixel)	# Use first pixel as label
else:
    for y in range(im.shape[0]):
        for x in range(im.shape[1]):
            if tm[y+1,x+1] > 0 and im[y,x] == 0:
                first_pixel = int(tm[y+1,x+1]) # Set first pixel value
                setlabel(x, y, l)
                l = l + 1 # Increment l for next label
                if l == 255: # If at max l value
                    l = 1 # Reset l to 1


if optv:
   print (im)

inimage.write(of)

Figure 36 - output image of nb.vx from vgrow with range = 77

The vgrow is executed against Figure 35 and the output is shown in Figure 36. The vgrow is executed with the "-p" flag and the output object region will be represented with the pixel value of each object in the original image. This algorithm starts from the top-left corner and finish to the bottom-right corner. It iterates each pixel and try to group the neighbouring pixels as a single region if it falls within a defined range.

Several runs of trial and errors were done to find the best range to be used for this image. When the range is too small, each object will be represented by several regions and the output will have more than 4 regions. When the range is too big, the objects were not be classified from each other and to number of regions in the image is less than 4.

The ideal range value is found to be 77, in which the objects are well-defined from each other and the background. We can also clearly see the shape of each of the screw and nut. If you take a look at the nut on the bottom-left of the image, we can see the hole in the middle of the nut representing the background. One aspect that this algorithm did poorly is on the region of the nut on the bottom-right, in which the algorithm could not separate the background in the hole of the nut with the nut itself. This is because the shadow in the original image causes the background to be of the same gray value with the nut itself, causing this poor region segmentation. Despite the imperfection, overall this algorithm did really well segmenting this image. The 4 regions or objects are clearly defined from the background and from each other. It looks like a solid algorithm to be used for image segmentation.

Next, this algorithm is executed on the shtl.vx image. This is an image where the thresholding algorithm did so poorly. What makes this iamge tricky to segment is that the background is of a gradient gray values from black to white, and that the main object is of a gray value within the background range. We will be exploring on whether region growing will provide a better performance.

The output is named edge.vx.

For this output image shown in Figure 41, the "-p" is not passed to the command. The output image is labeled sequentially. The range value is tested between 1 to 255. When the "r" value is low, between 1 to 20, the performance of the program is poor. The edge of the object is not segmented into a single region. However, starting from "r" to be 21 to 255, the region of the edge of the object is classified really well. The edge is able to be labeled as a single region. The range value of 21 is concluded to be one of the best, as it will classify the edge as a single region with the same label.

If you analyze Figure 41, we can see the tiny arrows in the background of the image. This is because the background of edge.vx is made up of "0" and "1" pixel values and they are detected as different regions. As a result, they are labeled as different regions and causes these tiny arrows visualization.

For visualization purpose, the output is processed using vcmap to uniquely color all regions. From the visualization in Figure 42, we can see that the edge is a single region. We can also see the tons of different regions in the background of the image.

Next, the output image is processsed to make it printable. This is done by running the vpix -neg command, which will revert the gray pixel values.

Concluding the performance of vgrow, it can be clearly seen that after the edge operation is done, the vgrow algorithm perform much better segmenting the shtl.vx image. We can see the major difference on the output images of using the original image vs edge-operated image as inputs. This means that in several cases, such as when an image is like shtl.vx, pre-processing may be required to allow a region-growing algorithm to have a much better performance and to provide a meaningful output.

To summarize this process, what happened is that a sobel edge operator is performed on the shtl.vx image. The output of that is an image with the detected edges of the object. Next, vgrow is used to segment the different regions in the image, using a specified range. With the right range, the region can be segmented in a way that the edge of the object (the shuttle) is of the same region and label. As a result, this process gives a great and meaningful output.

In this lab, we have explored two main image segmentation methods: thresholding and region growing. In thresholding itself, we learned about peakiness detection algorithm and iterative threshold selectrion algorith. For each of the methods, we have learned the strengths and weaknesses. We have also learned that pre-processing like edge detection before image segmentation may be beneficial to improve the output result.
